President Barack Obama has proclaimed April 21-27, 2013, as National Crime Victims' Rights Week in the United States. The proclamation emphasizes the need to provide support and services to crime victims, including care, counseling, and justice under the law. The president highlights the efforts of victim assistance programs and vows to continue supporting them. He mentions recent actions taken by his administration, such as signing the Violence Against Women Reauthorization Act and cracking down on financial crimes. The president also acknowledges the issue of gun violence and expresses the need for common-sense measures to address this problem. He calls upon all Americans to observe this week by participating in events that raise awareness of victims' rights and services, and by volunteering to help victims in their time of need.